Here's the full setup:

**AppShell.xaml**

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<Shell x:Class="MyMauiApp.AppShell"
       xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
       xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
       xmlns:views="clr-namespace:MyMauiApp.Views"
       FlyoutBehavior="Flyout"
       Title="MyMauiApp">

    <!-- Dashboard: single page, shown directly in the flyout -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Dashboard" Icon="dashboard.png">
        <ShellContent
            Title="Dashboard"
            ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:DashboardPage}"
            Route="dashboard" />
    </FlyoutItem>

    <!-- Products: flyout entry with two tabs -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Products" Icon="products.png">
        <Tab Title="Active">
            <ShellContent
                Title="Active"
                ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:ActiveProductsPage}"
                Route="active" />
        </Tab>
        <Tab Title="Archived">
            <ShellContent
                Title="Archived"
                ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:ArchivedProductsPage}"
                Route="archived" />
        </Tab>
    </FlyoutItem>

    <!-- Settings: single page in the flyout -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Settings" Icon="settings.png">
        <ShellContent
            Title="Settings"
            ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:SettingsPage}"
            Route="settings" />
    </FlyoutItem>

</Shell>
```

**AppShell.xaml.cs**

```csharp
namespace MyMauiApp;

public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Register the detail page so you can navigate with:
        //   await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage));
        // or with a parameter:
        //   await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?id={product.Id}");
        Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(Views.ProductDetailsPage), typeof(Views.ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

**Navigating from a list item** (e.g. in `ActiveProductsPage`):

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(object sender, SelectionChangedEventArgs e)
{
    if (e.CurrentSelection.FirstOrDefault() is Product product)
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?id={product.Id}");
    }
}
```

**Receiving the parameter** in `ProductDetailsPage`:

```csharp
[QueryProperty(nameof(ProductId), "id")]
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public string ProductId { get; set; }

    protected override void OnNavigatedTo(NavigatedToEventArgs args)
    {
        base.OnNavigatedTo(args);
        // Load product using ProductId
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`FlyoutItem`** = top-level flyout entry. Nesting multiple `<Tab>` elements inside one gives you the tab bar.
- **`ContentTemplate` + `DataTemplate`** = lazy-loads each page on first visit.
- **`Routing.RegisterRoute`** is required for pages *not* declared in the visual hierarchy (like detail pages you push onto the nav stack).
- Routes in `GoToAsync` are resolved relative to the current location, so the registered name alone is enough for a simple push.
